# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: security-hardening
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] The Linux PaX project first coined the term "ASLR", and published the first design and implementation of ASLR in July 2001 as a patch for the Linux kernel.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] It is seen as a complete implementation, providing a patch for kernel stack randomization since October 2002.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] The first mainstream operating system to support ASLR by default was OpenBSD version 3.4 in 2003, followed by Linux in 2005.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] Address space randomization hinders some types of security attacks by making it more difficult for an attacker to predict target addresses.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] For example, attackers trying to execute return-to-libc attacks must locate the code to be executed, while other attackers trying to execute shellcode injected on the stack have to find the stack first.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] In both cases, the system makes related memory-addresses unpredictable from the attackers' point of view.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] These values have to be guessed, and a mistaken guess is not usually recoverable due to the application crashing.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] Address space layout randomization is based upon the low chance of an attacker guessing the locations of randomly placed areas.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] Security is increased by increasing the search space.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] Thus, address space randomization is more effective when more entropy is present in the random offsets.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] Entropy is increased by either raising the amount of virtual memory area space over which the randomization occurs or reducing the period over which the randomization occurs.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] The period is typically implemented as small as possible, so most systems must increase VMA space randomization.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] To defeat the randomization, attackers must successfully guess the positions of all areas they wish to attack.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] For data areas such as stack and heap, where custom code or useful data can be loaded, more than one state can be attacked by using NOP slides for code or repeated copies of data.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] This allows an attack to succeed if the area is randomized to one of a handful of values.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] In contrast, code areas such as library base and main executable need to be discovered exactly.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] Often these areas are mixed, for example stack frames are injected onto the stack and a library is returned into.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] To calculate the probability of an attacker succeeding, a number of attempts α carried out without being interrupted by a signature-based IPS, law enforcement, or other factor must be assumed; in the case of brute forcing, the daemon cannot be restarted.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] The number of relevant bits and how many are being attacked in each attempt must also be calculated, leaving however many bits the attacker has to defeat.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] The following formulas represent the probability of success for a given set of α attempts on N bits of entropy.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] In many systems, $2^{N}$ can be in the thousands or millions.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] On 32-bit systems, a typical amount of entropy *N* is 8 bits.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] For 2004 computer speeds, Shacham and co-workers state "...
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] 16 bits of address randomization can be defeated by a brute force attack within minutes." (The authors' statement depends on the ability to attack the same application multiple times without any delay.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] Proper implementations of ASLR, like that included in grsecurity, provide several methods to make such brute force attacks infeasible.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] One method involves preventing an executable from executing for a configurable amount of time if it has crashed a certain number of times.) On modern 64-bit systems, these numbers typically reach the millions at least.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] Android, and possibly other systems, implement *Library Load Order Randomization*, a form of ASLR which randomizes the order in which libraries are loaded.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] An approximation of the number of bits of entropy supplied per needed library appears below; this does not yet account for varied library sizes, so the actual entropy gained is really somewhat higher.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] Attackers usually need only one library; the math is more complex with multiple libraries, and shown below as well.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] The case of an attacker using only one library is a simplification of the more complex formula for $l=1$ .
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] These values tend to be low even for large values of l, most importantly since attackers typically can use only the C standard library and thus one can often assume that $\beta \,=1$ .
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] However, even for a small number of libraries there are a few bits of entropy gained here; it is thus potentially interesting to combine library load order randomization with VMA address randomization to gain a few extra bits of entropy.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] These extra bits of entropy will not apply to other mmap() segments, only libraries.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] Attackers may make use of several methods to reduce the entropy present in a randomized address space, ranging from simple information leaks to attacking multiple bits of entropy per attack (such as by heap spraying).
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] There is little that can be done about this.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] It is possible to leak information about memory layout using format string vulnerabilities.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] Format string functions such as printf use a variable argument list to do their job; format specifiers describe what the argument list looks like.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] Because of the way arguments are typically passed, each format specifier moves closer to the top of the stack frame.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] Eventually, the return pointer and stack frame pointer can be extracted, revealing the address of a vulnerable library and the address of a known stack frame; this can eliminate library and stack randomization as an obstacle to an attacker.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] One can also decrease entropy in the stack or heap.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] The stack typically must be aligned to 16 bytes, and so this is the smallest possible randomization interval; while the heap must be page-aligned, typically 4096 bytes.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] When attempting an attack, it is possible to align duplicate attacks with these intervals; a NOP slide may be used with shellcode injection, and the string '`/bin/sh`' can be replaced with '`////////bin/sh`' for an arbitrary number of slashes when attempting to return to *system*.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] The number of bits removed is exactly $\log _{2}\!\left(n\right)$ for n intervals attacked.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] Such decreases are limited due to the amount of data in the stack or heap.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] The stack, for example, is typically limited to 8 MB and grows to much less; this allows for at most 19 bits, although a more conservative estimate would be around 8–10 bits corresponding to 4–16 KB of stack stuffing.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] The heap on the other hand is limited by the behavior of the memory allocator; in the case of glibc, allocations above 128 KB are created using mmap, limiting attackers to 5 bits of reduction.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] This is also a limiting factor when brute forcing; although the number of attacks to perform can be reduced, the size of the attacks is increased enough that the behavior could in some circumstances become apparent to intrusion detection systems.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] ASLR-protected addresses can be leaked by various side channels, removing mitigation utility.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] Recent attacks have used information leaked by the CPU branch target predictor buffer (BTB) or memory management unit (MMU) walking page tables.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] It is not clear if this class of ASLR attack can be mitigated.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] If they cannot, the benefit of ASLR is reduced or eliminated.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] In August 2024 a paper was published with an empirical analysis of major desktop platforms, including Linux, macOS, and Windows, by examining the variability in the placement of memory objects across various processes, threads, and system restarts.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] The results show that while some systems as of 2024, like Linux distributions, provide robust randomization, others, like Windows and macOS, often fail to adequately randomize key areas like executable code and libraries.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] Moreover, they found a significant reduction in the entropy of libraries after the Linux 5.18 version and identify correlation paths that an attacker could leverage to reduce exploitation complexity significantly.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] Several mainstream, general-purpose operating systems implement ASLR.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] Android 4.0 Ice Cream Sandwich provides address space layout randomization (ASLR) to help protect system and third-party applications from exploits due to memory-management issues.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] Position-independent executable support was added in Android 4.1.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] Android 5.0 dropped non-PIE support and requires all dynamically linked binaries to be position independent.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] Library load ordering randomization was accepted into the Android open-source project on 26 October 2015, and was included in the Android 7.0 release.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] DragonFly BSD has an implementation of ASLR based upon OpenBSD's model, added in 2010.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] It is off by default, and can be enabled by setting the sysctl vm.randomize_mmap to 1.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] Support for ASLR appeared in FreeBSD 13.0.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] Apple introduced ASLR in iOS 4.3 (released March 2011).
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] The randomized kernel base is `0x01000000 + ((1+0xRR) * 0x00200000)`, where `0xRR` is a random byte from SHA1 (random data) generated by iBoot (the 2nd-stage iOS Boot Loader).
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] The Linux kernel enabled a weak form of ASLR by default since the kernel version 2.6.12, released in June 2005.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] The PaX and Exec Shield patchsets to the Linux kernel provide more complete implementations.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] The Exec Shield patch for Linux supplies 19 bits of stack entropy on a period of 16 bytes, and 8 bits of mmap base randomization on a period of 1 page of 4096 bytes.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] This places the stack base in an area 8 MB wide containing 524,288 possible positions, and the mmap base in an area 1 MB wide containing 256 possible positions.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] ASLR can be disabled for a specific process by changing its execution domain, using `personality(2)`.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] A number of sysctl options control the behavior of mainline ASLR.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] For example, `kernel.randomize_va_space` controls *what* to randomize; the strongest option is 2.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] `vm.mmap_rnd_bits` controls how many bits to randomize for mmap.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] Position-independent executable (PIE) implements a random base address for the main executable binary and has been in place since April 18, 2004.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] It provides the same address randomness to the main executable as being used for the shared libraries.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] The PIE feature cannot be used together with the prelink feature for the same executable.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] The prelink tool implements randomization at prelink time rather than runtime, because by design prelink aims to handle relocating libraries before the dynamic linker has to, which allows the relocation to occur once for many runs of the program.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] As a result, real address space randomization would defeat the purpose of prelinking.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] In 2014, Marco-Gisbert and Ripoll disclosed *offset2lib* technique that weakens Linux ASLR for PIE executables.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] Linux kernels load PIE executables right after their libraries; as a result, there is a fixed offset between the executable and the library functions.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] If an attacker finds a way to find the address of a function in the executable, the library addresses are also known.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] They demonstrated an attack that finds the address in fewer than 400 tries.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] They proposed a new `randomize_va_space=3` option to randomize the placement of the executable relative to the library, but it is yet to be incorporated into the upstream as of 2024.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] The Linux kernel 5.18 released May 2022 reduced the effectiveness of both 32-bit and 64-bit implementations.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] Linux filesystems call `thp_get_unmapped_area` to respond to a file-backed mmap.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] With a change in 5.18, files greater than 2 MiB are made to return 2 MiB-aligned addresses, so they can be potentially backed by huge pages.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] For 32-bit Linux, many distributions show no randomization *at all* in the placement of the libc.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] For 64-bit Linux, the 28 bits of entropy is reduced to 19 bits.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] In response, Ubuntu has increased its `mmap_rnd_bits` setting.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] Martin Doucha added a Linux Test Project testcase to detect this issue.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] Kernel address space layout randomization (KASLR) enables address space randomization for the Linux kernel image by randomizing where the kernel code is placed at boot time.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] KASLR was merged into the Linux kernel mainline in kernel version 3.14, released on 30 March 2014.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] When compiled in, it can be disabled at boot time by specifying nokaslr as one of the kernel's boot parameters.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] There are several side-channel attacks in x86 processors that could leak kernel addresses.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] In late 2017, kernel page-table isolation (KPTI aka KAISER) was developed to defeat these attacks.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] However, this method cannot protect against side-channel attacks utilizing collisions in branch predictor structures.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] As of 2021, finer grained kernel address space layout randomization (or function granular KASLR, FGKASLR) is a planned extension of KASLR to randomize down to the function level by placing functions in separate sections and reordering them at boot time.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] Microsoft's Windows Vista (released *to manufacturing* November 2006, generally available January 2007) and later have ASLR enabled only for executables and dynamic link libraries that are specifically linked to be ASLR-enabled.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] For compatibility, it is not enabled by default for other applications.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] Typically, only older software is incompatible and ASLR can be fully enabled by editing a registry entry `HKLM\SYSTEM\CurrentControlSet\Control\Session Manager\Memory Management\MoveImages`, or by installing Microsoft's Enhanced Mitigation Experience Toolkit.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] The locations of the heap, stack, Process Environment Block, and Thread Environment Block are also randomized.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] A security whitepaper from Symantec noted that ASLR in 32-bit Windows Vista may not be as robust as expected, and Microsoft has acknowledged a weakness in its implementation.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] Host-based intrusion prevention systems such as *WehnTrust* and *Ozone* also offer ASLR for Windows XP and Windows Server 2003 operating systems.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] Complete details of Ozone's implementation are not available.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] It was noted in February 2012 that ASLR on 32-bit Windows systems prior to Windows 8 can have its effectiveness reduced in low memory situations.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] A similar effect also had been achieved on Linux in the same research.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] The test code caused the Mac OS X 10.7.3 system to kernel panic, so it was left unclear about its ASLR behavior in this scenario.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] Support for ASLR in userland appeared in NetBSD 5.0 (released April 2009), and was enabled by default in NetBSD-current in April 2016.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] Kernel ASLR support on amd64 was added in NetBSD-current in October 2017, making NetBSD the first BSD system to support KASLR.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] In 2003, OpenBSD became the first mainstream operating system to support a strong form of ASLR and to activate it by default.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] OpenBSD completed its ASLR support in 2008 when it added support for PIE binaries.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] OpenBSD 4.4's malloc(3) was designed to improve security by taking advantage of ASLR and gap page features implemented as part of OpenBSD's `mmap` system call, and to detect use-after-free bugs.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] Released in 2013, OpenBSD 5.3 was the first mainstream operating system to enable position-independent executables by default on multiple hardware platforms, and OpenBSD 5.7 activated position-independent static binaries (Static-PIE) by default.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] In Mac OS X Leopard 10.5 (released October 2007), Apple introduced randomization for system libraries.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] In Mac OS X Lion 10.7 (released July 2011), Apple expanded their implementation to cover all applications, stating "address space layout randomization (ASLR) has been improved for all applications.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] As of OS X Mountain Lion 10.8 (released July 2012) and later, the entire system including the kernel as well as kexts and zones are randomly relocated during system boot.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] ASLR has been introduced in Solaris beginning with Solaris 11.1 (released October 2012).
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] ASLR in Solaris 11.1 can be set system-wide, per zone, or on a per-binary basis.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] A side-channel attack utilizing branch target buffer was demonstrated to bypass ASLR protection.
[src:security-hardening/address-space-layout-randomization] In 2017, an attack named "ASLR⊕Cache" was demonstrated which could defeat ASLR in a web browser using JavaScript.
[src:security-hardening/attack-surface] The **attack surface** of a software environment is the sum of the different points (for "attack vectors") where an unauthorized user (the "attacker") can try to enter data to, extract data from, or control a device or critical software in an environment.
[src:security-hardening/attack-surface] Keeping the attack surface as small as possible is a basic security measure.
[src:security-hardening/attack-surface] Worldwide digital change has accelerated the size, scope, and composition of an organization's attack surface.
[src:security-hardening/attack-surface] The size of an attack surface may fluctuate over time, adding and subtracting assets and digital systems (e.g. websites, hosts, cloud and mobile apps, etc.).
[src:security-hardening/attack-surface] Attack surface sizes can change rapidly as well.
[src:security-hardening/attack-surface] Digital assets eschew the physical requirements of traditional network devices, servers, data centers, and on-premise networks.
[src:security-hardening/attack-surface] This leads to attack surfaces changing rapidly, based on the organization's needs and the availability of digital services to accomplish it.
[src:security-hardening/attack-surface] Attack surface scope also varies from organization to organization.
[src:security-hardening/attack-surface] With the rise of digital supply chains, interdependencies, and globalization, an organization's attack surface has a broader scope of concern (viz. vectors for cyberattacks).
[src:security-hardening/attack-surface] Due to the increase in the countless potential vulnerable points each enterprise has, there has been increasing advantage for hackers and attackers as they only need to find one vulnerable point to succeed in their attack.
[src:security-hardening/attack-surface] One approach to improving information security is to reduce the attack surface of a system or software.
[src:security-hardening/attack-surface] The basic strategies of attack surface reduction include the following: reduce the amount of code running, reduce entry points available to untrusted users, and eliminate services requested by relatively few users.
[src:security-hardening/attack-surface] By having less code available to unauthorized actors, there tend to be fewer failures.
[src:security-hardening/attack-surface] By turning off unnecessary functionality, there are fewer security risks.
[src:security-hardening/attack-surface] Although attack surface reduction helps prevent security failures, it does not mitigate the amount of damage an attacker could inflict once a vulnerability is found.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] In computer security, **executable-space protection** marks memory regions as non-executable, such that an attempt to execute machine code in these regions will cause an exception.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] It relies on hardware features such as the NX bit (no-execute bit), or on software emulation when hardware support is unavailable.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] Software emulation often introduces a performance cost, or overhead (extra processing time or resources), while hardware-based NX bit implementations have no measurable performance impact.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] The Burroughs large systems, starting with the Burroughs 5000 introduced in 1961, implemented executable-space protection using a tagged architecture.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] All accesses to code and data took place through descriptors, which had memory tags preventing them from being modified; descriptors for code did not allow the code to be modified, and descriptors for data did not allow the data to be executed as code.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] Today, operating systems use executable-space protection to mark writable memory areas, such as the stack and heap, as non-executable, helping to prevent buffer overflow exploits.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] These attacks rely on some part of memory, usually the stack, being both writable and executable; if it is not, the attack fails.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] Many operating systems implement or have an available executable space protection policy.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] Here is a list of such systems in alphabetical order, each with technologies ordered from newest to oldest.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] A technology supplying Architecture Independent emulation will be functional on all processors which aren't hardware supported.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] The "Other Supported" line is for processors which allow some grey-area method, where an explicit NX bit doesn't exist yet hardware allows one to be emulated in some way.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] As of Android 2.3 and later, architectures which support it have non-executable pages by default, including non-executable stack and heap.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] Initial support for the NX bit, on x86-64 and IA-32 processors that support it, first appeared in FreeBSD -CURRENT on June 8, 2004.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] It has been in FreeBSD releases since the 5.3 release.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] The Linux kernel supports the NX bit on x86-64 and IA-32 processors that support it, such as modern 64-bit processors made by AMD, Intel, Transmeta and VIA.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] The support for this feature in the 64-bit mode on x86-64 CPUs was added in 2004 by Andi Kleen, and later the same year, Ingo Molnár added support for it in 32-bit mode on 64-bit CPUs.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] These features have been part of the Linux kernel mainline since the release of kernel version 2.6.8 in August 2004.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] Other processors that do not support PAE are AMD K6 and earlier, Transmeta Crusoe, VIA C3 and earlier, and Geode GX and LX.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] VMware Workstation versions older than 4.0, Parallels Workstation versions older than 4.0, and Microsoft Virtual PC and Virtual Server do not support PAE on the guest.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] Fedora Core 6 and Ubuntu 9.10 and later provide a kernel-PAE package which supports PAE and NX.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] NX memory protection has always been available in Ubuntu for any systems that had the hardware to support it and ran the 64-bit kernel or the 32-bit server kernel.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] The 32-bit PAE desktop kernel (linux-image-generic-pae) in Ubuntu 9.10 and later, also provides the PAE mode needed for hardware with the NX CPU feature.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] For systems that lack NX hardware, the 32-bit kernels now provide an approximation of the NX CPU feature via software emulation that can help block many exploits an attacker might run from stack or heap memory.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] Non-execute functionality has also been present for other non-x86 processors supporting this functionality for many releases.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] Red Hat kernel developer Ingo Molnár released a Linux kernel patch named Exec Shield to approximate and utilize NX functionality on 32-bit x86 CPUs.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] The Exec Shield patch was released to the Linux kernel mailing list on May 2, 2003, but was rejected for merging with the base kernel because it involved some intrusive changes to core code in order to handle the complex parts of the emulation.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] Exec Shield's legacy CPU support approximates NX emulation by tracking the upper code segment limit.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] This imposes only a few cycles of overhead during context switches, which is for all intents and purposes immeasurable.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] For legacy CPUs without an NX bit, Exec Shield fails to protect pages below the code segment limit; an mprotect() call to mark higher memory, such as the stack, executable will mark all memory below that limit executable as well.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] Thus, in these situations, Exec Shield's schemes fails.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] This is the cost of Exec Shield's low overhead.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] Exec Shield checks for two ELF header markings, which dictate whether the stack or heap needs to be executable.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] These are called PT_GNU_STACK and PT_GNU_HEAP respectively.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] Exec Shield allows these controls to be set for both binary executables and for libraries; if an executable loads a library requiring a given restriction relaxed, the executable will inherit that marking and have that restriction relaxed.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] The PaX NX technology can emulate NX functionality, or use a hardware NX bit.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] PaX works on x86 CPUs that do not have the NX bit, such as 32-bit x86.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] The Linux kernel still does not ship with PaX (as of May, 2007); the patch must be merged manually.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] PaX provides two methods of NX bit emulation, called SEGMEXEC and PAGEEXEC.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] The SEGMEXEC method imposes a measurable but low overhead, typically less than 1%, which is a constant scalar incurred due to the virtual memory mirroring used for the separation between execution and data accesses.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] SEGMEXEC also has the effect of halving the task's virtual address space, allowing the task to access less memory than it normally could.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] This is not a problem until the task requires access to more than half the normal address space, which is rare.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] SEGMEXEC does not cause programs to use more system memory (i.e.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] RAM), it only restricts how much they can access.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] On 32-bit CPUs, this becomes 1.5 GB rather than 3 GB.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] PaX supplies a method similar to Exec Shield's approximation in the PAGEEXEC as a speedup; however, when higher memory is marked executable, this method loses its protections.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] In these cases, PaX falls back to the older, variable-overhead method used by PAGEEXEC to protect pages below the CS limit, which may become quite a high-overhead operation in certain memory access patterns.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] When the PAGEEXEC method is used on a CPU supplying a hardware NX bit, the hardware NX bit is used, thus no significant overhead is incurred.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] PaX supplies mprotect() restrictions to prevent programs from marking memory in ways that produce memory useful for a potential exploit.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] This policy causes certain applications to cease to function, but it can be disabled for affected programs.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] PaX ignores both PT_GNU_STACK and PT_GNU_HEAP.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] In the past, PaX had a configuration option to honor these settings but that option has been removed for security reasons, as it was deemed not useful.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] The same results of PT_GNU_STACK can normally be attained by disabling mprotect() restrictions, as the program will normally mprotect() the stack on load.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] This may not always be true; for situations where this fails, simply disabling both PAGEEXEC and SEGMEXEC will effectively remove all executable space restrictions, giving the task the same protections on its executable space as a non-PaX system.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] macOS for Intel supports the NX bit on all CPUs supported by Apple (from Mac OS X 10.4.4 – the first Intel release – onwards).
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] Mac OS X 10.4 only supported NX stack protection.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] In Mac OS X 10.5, all 64-bit executables have NX stack and heap; W^X protection.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] This includes x86-64 (Core 2 or later) and 64-bit PowerPC on the G5 Macs.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] As of NetBSD 2.0 and later (December 9, 2004), architectures which support it have non-executable stack and heap.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] Architectures that have per-page granularity consist of: alpha, amd64, hppa, i386 (with PAE), powerpc (ibm4xx), sh5, sparc (sun4m, sun4d), sparc64.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] Architectures that can only support these with region granularity are: i386 (without PAE), other powerpc (such as macppc).
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] Other architectures do not benefit from non-executable stack or heap; NetBSD does not by default use any software emulation to offer these features on those architectures.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] A technology in the OpenBSD operating system, known as W^X, marks writable pages by default as non-executable on processors that support that.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] On 32-bit x86 processors, the code segment is set to include only part of the address space, to provide some level of executable space protection.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] OpenBSD 3.3 shipped May 1, 2003, and was the first to include W^X.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] Solaris has supported globally disabling stack execution on SPARC processors since Solaris 2.6 (1997); in Solaris 9 (2002), support for disabling stack execution on a per-executable basis was added.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] The first implementation of a non-executable stack for Windows (NT 4.0, 2000 and XP) was published by SecureWave via their SecureStack product in 2001, based on the work of PaX.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] Starting with Windows XP Service Pack 2 (2004) and Windows Server 2003 Service Pack 1 (2005), the NX features were implemented for the first time on the x86 architecture.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] Executable space protection on Windows is called "Data Execution Prevention" (DEP).
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] Under Windows XP or Server 2003 NX protection was used on critical Windows services exclusively by default.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] If the x86 processor supported this feature in hardware, then the NX features were turned on automatically in Windows XP/Server 2003 by default.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] If the feature was not supported by the x86 processor, then no protection was given.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] Early implementations of DEP provided no address space layout randomization (ASLR), which allowed potential return-to-libc attacks that could have been feasibly used to disable DEP during an attack.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] The PaX documentation elaborates on why ASLR is necessary; a proof-of-concept was produced detailing a method by which DEP could be circumvented in the absence of ASLR.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] It may be possible to develop a successful attack if the address of prepared data such as corrupted images or MP3s can be known by the attacker.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] Microsoft added ASLR functionality in Windows Vista and Windows Server 2008.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] On this platform, DEP is implemented through the automatic use of PAE kernel in 32-bit Windows and the native support on 64-bit kernels.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] Windows Vista DEP works by marking certain parts of memory as being intended to hold only data, which the NX or XD bit enabled processor then understands as non-executable.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] In Windows, from version Vista, whether DEP is enabled or disabled for a particular process can be viewed on the *Processes/Details* tab in the Windows Task Manager.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] Windows implements software DEP (without the use of the NX bit) through Microsoft's "Safe Structured Exception Handling" (SafeSEH).
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] For properly compiled applications, SafeSEH checks that, when an exception is raised during program execution, the exception's handler is one defined by the application as it was originally compiled.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] The effect of this protection is that an attacker is not able to add his own exception handler which he has stored in a data page through unchecked program input.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] When NX is supported, it is enabled by default.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] Windows allows programs to control which pages disallow execution through its API as well as through the section headers in a PE file.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] In the API, runtime access to the NX bit is exposed through the Win32 API calls VirtualAlloc[Ex] and VirtualProtect[Ex].
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] Each page may be individually flagged as executable or non-executable.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] Despite the lack of previous x86 hardware support, both executable and non-executable page settings have been provided since the beginning.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] On pre-NX CPUs, the presence of the 'executable' attribute has no effect.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] It was documented as if it did function, and, as a result, most programmers used it properly.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] In the PE file format, each section can specify its executability.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] The execution flag has existed since the beginning of the format and standard linkers have always used this flag correctly, even long before the NX bit.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] Because of this, Windows is able to enforce the NX bit on old programs.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] Assuming the programmer complied with "best practices", applications should work correctly now that NX is actually enforced.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] Only in a few cases have there been problems; Microsoft's own .NET Runtime had problems with the NX bit and was updated.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] In Microsoft's Xbox, although the CPU does not have the NX bit, newer versions of the XDK set the code segment limit to the beginning of the kernel's **.data** section (no code should be after this point in normal circumstances).
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] Starting with version 51xx, this change was also implemented into the kernel of new Xboxes.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] This broke the techniques old exploits used to become a terminate-and-stay-resident program.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] However, new exploits were quickly released supporting this new kernel version because the fundamental vulnerability in the Xbox kernel was unaffected.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] Where code is written and executed at runtime—a JIT compiler is a prominent example—the compiler can potentially be used to produce exploit code (e.g. using JIT Spray) that has been flagged for execution and therefore would not be trapped.
[src:security-hardening/data-execution-prevention] Return-oriented programming can allow an attacker to execute arbitrary code even when executable space protection is enforced.
[src:security-hardening/defense-in-depth-computing] The idea behind the defense in depth approach is to defend a system against any particular attack using several independent methods.
[src:security-hardening/defense-in-depth-computing] It is a layering tactic, conceived by the National Security Agency (NSA) as a comprehensive approach to information and electronic security.
[src:security-hardening/defense-in-depth-computing] Defense in depth is sometimes thought of as forming the layers of an onion, with data at the core of the onion, people the next outer layer of the onion, and network security, host-based security, and application security forming the outermost layers of the onion.
[src:security-hardening/defense-in-depth-computing] Defense in depth can be divided into three overarching areas: Physical, Technical, and Administrative.
[src:security-hardening/defense-in-depth-computing] Physical controls are anything that physically limits or prevents access to IT systems.
[src:security-hardening/defense-in-depth-computing] Examples of physical defensive security are: fences, guards, dogs, and CCTV systems.
[src:security-hardening/defense-in-depth-computing] Technical controls are hardware or software whose purpose is to protect systems and resources.
[src:security-hardening/defense-in-depth-computing] Examples of technical controls include disk encryption, file integrity software, authentication, network security controls, antiviruses, and behavioural analysis software.
[src:security-hardening/defense-in-depth-computing] In the event that one layer of defence fails, defense in depth aims to ensure network security via a second-line of defence.
[src:security-hardening/defense-in-depth-computing] For example, if an attacker penetrates a computer system at a given OSI layer (e.g.
[src:security-hardening/defense-in-depth-computing] Layer 3), a redundancy should exist at another layer (Layer 7) to ensure layered defense.
[src:security-hardening/defense-in-depth-computing] Administrative controls are the organization's policies and procedures and govern the organisation's human resources, technology, and operations.
[src:security-hardening/hardening-computing] In computer security, **hardening** or **system hardening** is usually the process of securing a system by making it a 'hard target' by reducing its attack surface vulnerabilities.
[src:security-hardening/hardening-computing] The attack surface is larger when a system performs more functions; in principle a single-function system is more secure than a multipurpose one.
[src:security-hardening/hardening-computing] Hardening is considered an important component of cybersecurity.
[src:security-hardening/hardening-computing] Reducing available ways of attack typically includes changing default passwords, the removal of unnecessary software, unnecessary usernames or logins, and the disabling or removal of unnecessary services.
[src:security-hardening/hardening-computing] It may also involve patching vulnerabilities and switching off ancillary services that are not essential.
[src:security-hardening/hardening-computing] Hardening measures can also include setting up intrusion prevention systems, disabling or restricting accounts, reducing file system permissions, using encrypted network connections and enabling host-based network security.
[src:security-hardening/hardening-computing] Binary hardening is a security technique in which binary executables are analyzed and modified to protect against common exploits.
[src:security-hardening/hardening-computing] Binary hardening is independent of compilers and involves the entire toolchain.
[src:security-hardening/hardening-computing] For example, one binary hardening technique is to detect potential buffer overflows and to substitute the existing code with safer code.
[src:security-hardening/hardening-computing] The advantage of manipulating binaries is that vulnerabilities in legacy code can be fixed automatically without the need for source code, which may be unavailable or obfuscated.
[src:security-hardening/hardening-computing] Secondly, the same techniques can be applied to binaries from multiple compilers, some of which may be less secure than others.
[src:security-hardening/hardening-computing] Binary hardening often involves the non-deterministic modification of control flow and instruction addresses so as to prevent attackers from successfully reusing program code to perform exploits.
[src:security-hardening/principle-of-least-privilege] The principle means giving any user accounts or processes only those privileges which are essentially vital to perform its intended functions.
[src:security-hardening/principle-of-least-privilege] For example, a user account for the sole purpose of creating backups does not need to install software: hence, it has rights only to run backup and backup-related applications.
[src:security-hardening/principle-of-least-privilege] Any other privileges, such as installing new software, are blocked.
[src:security-hardening/principle-of-least-privilege] The principle applies also to a personal computer user who usually does work in a normal user account, and opens a privileged, password protected account only when the situation absolutely demands it.
[src:security-hardening/principle-of-least-privilege] When applied to users, the terms *least user access* or *least-privileged user account* (LUA) are also used, referring to the concept that all user accounts should run with as few privileges as possible, and also launch applications with as few privileges as possible.
[src:security-hardening/principle-of-least-privilege] The principle (of least privilege) is widely recognized as an important design consideration towards enhancing and giving a much needed 'Boost' to the protection of data and functionality from faults (fault tolerance) and malicious behavior.
[src:security-hardening/principle-of-least-privilege] In practice, there exist multiple competing definitions of true (least privilege).
[src:security-hardening/principle-of-least-privilege] As program complexity increases rapidly, so do the number of potential issues, rendering a predictive approach impractical.
[src:security-hardening/principle-of-least-privilege] Examples include the values of variables it may process, addresses it will need, or the precise time such things will be required.
[src:security-hardening/principle-of-least-privilege] Object capability systems allow, for instance, deferring granting a single-use privilege until the time when it will be used.
[src:security-hardening/principle-of-least-privilege] Currently, the closest practical approach is to eliminate privileges that can be manually evaluated as unnecessary.
[src:security-hardening/principle-of-least-privilege] The resulting set of privileges typically exceeds the true minimum required privileges for the process.
[src:security-hardening/principle-of-least-privilege] Another limitation is the granularity of control that the operating environment has over privileges for an individual process.
[src:security-hardening/principle-of-least-privilege] In practice, it is rarely possible to control a process's access to memory, processing time, I/O device addresses or modes with the precision needed to facilitate only the precise set of privileges a process will require.
[src:security-hardening/principle-of-least-privilege] Denning, in his paper "Fault Tolerant Operating Systems", set it in a broader perspective among "The four fundamental principles of fault tolerance".
[src:security-hardening/principle-of-least-privilege] "Dynamic assignments of privileges" was earlier discussed by Roger Needham in 1972.
[src:security-hardening/principle-of-least-privilege] Historically, the oldest instance of (least privilege) is probably the source code of *login.c*, which begins execution with super-user permissions and—the instant they are no longer necessary—dismisses them via *setuid()* with a non-zero argument as demonstrated in the Version 6 Unix source code.
[src:security-hardening/principle-of-least-privilege] The kernel always runs with maximum privileges since it is the operating system core and has hardware access.
[src:security-hardening/principle-of-least-privilege] One of the principal responsibilities of an operating system, particularly a multi-user operating system, is management of the hardware's availability and requests to access it from running processes.
[src:security-hardening/principle-of-least-privilege] When the kernel crashes, the mechanisms by which it maintains state also fail.
[src:security-hardening/principle-of-least-privilege] Therefore, even if there is a way for the CPU to recover without a hard reset, security continues to be enforced, but the operating system cannot properly respond to the failure because it was not possible to detect the failure.
[src:security-hardening/principle-of-least-privilege] This is because kernel execution either halted or the program counter resumed execution from somewhere in an endless, and—usually—non-functional loop.
[src:security-hardening/principle-of-least-privilege] This would be akin to either experiencing amnesia (kernel execution failure) or being trapped in a closed maze that always returns to the starting point (closed loops).
[src:security-hardening/principle-of-least-privilege] If execution picks up after the crash by loading and running trojan code, the author of the trojan code can usurp control of all processes.
[src:security-hardening/principle-of-least-privilege] The principle of least privilege forces code to run with the lowest privilege/permission level possible.
[src:security-hardening/principle-of-least-privilege] This means that the code that resumes the code execution-whether trojan or simply code execution picking up from an unexpected location—would not have the ability to perform malicious or undesirable processes.
[src:security-hardening/principle-of-least-privilege] One method used to accomplish this can be implemented in the microprocessor hardware.
[src:security-hardening/principle-of-least-privilege] For example, in the Intel x86 architecture the manufacturer designed four (ring 0 through ring 3) running "modes" with graduated degrees of access-much like security clearance systems in defence and intelligence agencies.
[src:security-hardening/principle-of-least-privilege] As implemented in some operating systems, processes execute with a *potential privilege set* and an *active privilege set*.
[src:security-hardening/principle-of-least-privilege] Such privilege sets are inherited from the parent as determined by the semantics of *fork()*.
[src:security-hardening/principle-of-least-privilege] An executable file that performs a privileged function—thereby technically constituting a component of the TCB, and concomitantly termed a trusted program or trusted process—may also be marked with a set of privileges.
[src:security-hardening/principle-of-least-privilege] This is a logical extension of the notions of set user ID and set group ID.
[src:security-hardening/principle-of-least-privilege] The inheritance of file privileges by a process are determined by the semantics of the *exec()* family of system calls.
[src:security-hardening/principle-of-least-privilege] The precise manner in which potential process privileges, actual process privileges, and file privileges interact can become complex.
[src:security-hardening/principle-of-least-privilege] In practice, least privilege is practiced by forcing a process to run with only those privileges required by the task.
[src:security-hardening/principle-of-least-privilege] Adherence to this model is quite complex as well as error-prone.
[src:security-hardening/principle-of-least-privilege] Least privilege has also been interpreted in the context of distribution of discretionary access control (DAC) permissions, for example asserting that giving user U read/write access to file F violates least privilege if U can complete their authorized tasks with only read permission.
